aa(lp275
VSo I've mentioned WikiLeaks, because surely what could be
p276
aVmore open than publishing all the material?
p277
aVBecause that is what Julian Assange did.
p278
aVHe wasn't content with the way the newspapers published it
p279
aVto be safe and legal. He threw it all out there.
p280
aVThat did end up with vulnerable people in Afghanistan
p281
aVbeing exposed. It also meant that the Belarussian dictator
p282
aVwas given a handy list of all the pro-democracy campaigners
p283
aVin that country who had spoken to the U.S. government.
p284
aVIs that radical openness? I say it's not, because for me,
p285
aVwhat it means, it doesn't mean abdicating power,
p286
aVresponsibility, accountability, it's actually being a partner
p287
aVwith power. It's about sharing responsibility,
p288
aVsharing accountability. Also, the fact that
p289
aVhe threatened to sue me because I got a leak of his leaks,
p290
aVI thought that showed a remarkable sort of inconsistency
p291
aVin ideology, to be honest, as well. (Laughs)
